    {
      "id": "74b9695a77dd64097e98778a29dd6a92e7e504e6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2018-11-21 03:50:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "37555d7af7930d43261a36a8cfcdbd1ef53c5e65",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2018-11-21 04:00:30.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: -Code-Review\n\nErr, so... I guess I am missing something here.\n\nCan why do we have the 1:1 mapping here again? The LUSTRE_BLAH is supposed to be little endian representation so that no matter your host byteorder, you get correct one after conversion from network.\n\nWhen say a bigendian host wants to send ELDLM_LOCK_CHANGED with your patch in, that makes it place a bigendian value for 300 into the packet and if the receiving end is little endian, it receives some garbage high value instead now. Hilarity ensues.\n\nDid you do any cross-endianness testing with this patch? As is it looks like it would not work and you need to add corresponding LUSTRE_XXX errnos in lustre/include/lustre_errno.h",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "c47a742f31e57cde86ad6414993098d7d394b6fb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 358,
        "name": "Ann Koehler",
        "email": "amk@cray.com",
        "username": "amk",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2018-11-21 16:21:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nThis mapping is not for \"endianess\". The lustre_errno mapping functions handle the case where different architectures use different values for errnos. The bug being fixed is that ELDLM errnos are mapped to EIO on non-x86 architectures breaking glimpse lock callback.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "30dfd149f88558b9ca2a92f54fc1ec61c49a652f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2018-11-21 17:09:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2\n\nok",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
